land":"Buckinghamshire, England","Farnham, Surrey, England":"Farnham, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Wingrave, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wingrave, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vincent","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Vincent</i>, Latin <i>Vincentius</i>, a derivative of <i>vincens</i>, genitive <i>vincentis</i>, present participle of <i>vincere</i> ‘to conquer’. The name was borne by a 3rd-century Spanish martyr widely venerated in the Middle Ages and by a 5th-century monk and writer of Lérins, as well as various other early Christian saints.","Irish: the English surname (see 1 above) has been established in the south of Ireland since the 17th century, and has also been adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Dhuibhinse</b> ‘son of the dark man of the island’.","History: The surname <i>Vincent</i> of French origin (see 1 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"St. Vincent","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Leandre, Monique.","French (<b>Saint-Vincent</b>): habitational name from any of several places in various parts of France named Saint-Vincent (from the dedication of their churches to Saint Vincent), or a nickname with the prefix <i>Saint</i> as an (ironic) attachment to the personal name or surname   Vincent  .","History: Vincent Chamereau <i>dit</i> Saint-Vincent from Paris, France, married Marie-Thérèse Auban in Pierrefonds, QC, in 1752."]},{"name":"Venson","meanings":["English: altered form of   Vincent  .","French (Lot-et-Garonne): probably from a vernacular diminutive of the personal name   Vincent  . This surname is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Vince","meanings":["English (East Anglia): from a short form of the personal name   Vincent  .","Hungarian: variant of   Vincze  ."]},{"name":"Vicencio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Anamaria, Javier, Jesus, Jorge, Juan, Manuel, Mario, Adriana, Alfonso, Amado, Baudelio.","Hispanic (mainly Mexico, Chile, and the Philippines); Portuguese (<b>Vicêncio</b>): from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Vincentius</i> (see   Vincent  ), a variant of   Vicente  ."]},{"name":"Vincze","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Arpad, Laszlo, Aranka, Attila, Bela, Ildiko, Kalman, Lajos, Mihaly, Miklos, Sandor, Zsolt.  Jewish Aron.","Hungarian: from the personal name <i>Vince</i>, Hungarian form of   Vincent  .","Jewish (from Hungary): adoption of the Hungarian surname in 1 above because it has some sounds in common with the original German-based surname."]},{"name":"Sensel","meanings":["South German: probably from a pet form of the Latin personal name <i>Vincens</i> (see   Vincent  ).","German: habitational name from any of the places called Senseln in former East Prussia and Bohemia."]},{"name":"Vicente","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Armando, Carlos, Juan, Antonio, Sergio, Enrique, Jorge, Luis, Mario, Adriano, Esteban.  Portuguese Joaquim, Paulo, Aderito, Anabela, Joao, Martinho, Vasco.","Spanish and Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Vicente</i>, an equivalent of   Vincent  ."]},{"name":"Vincelette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aime, Alphonse, Fernand, Normand.","Americanized form of French <b>Vincelet</b>: derivative of   Vincent  . It reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]},{"name":"Vincenti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Aldo, Angelo, Attilio, Carlo, Dante, Gino, Marco, Querino, Vito.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Vincente</i> (see   Vincent  ). This surname is also found in Corsica and southern France."]},{"name":"Vincenzo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Silvio, Angelo, Emilio, Fortunato, Mario.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Vincenzo</i>, a cognate of<i>Vincente</i> (see   Vincent  )."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Vincent was born in 1540, in Wingrave, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with John Streame I. She died about 1612, in Farnham, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 73."},"et":{"1540–Abt. 1612":"1540–umbes 1612","1540–1618":"1540–1618","1560–1624":"1560–1624","1560–1629":"1560–1629","1540–1612":"1540–1612","1624":"1624","1612":"1612","Abt. 1612":"umbes 1612","1540":"1540","1560":"1560","1629":"1629","1618":"1618","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Farnham, Surrey, England":"Farnham, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wingrave, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wingrave, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1540–Abt. 1612":"1540–noin 1612","1540–1618":"1540–1618","1560–1624":"1560–1624","1560–1629":"1560–1629","1540–1612":"1540–1612","1624":"1624","1612":"1612","Abt. 1612":"noin 1612","1540":"1540","1560":"1560","1629":"1629","1618":"1618","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Farnham, Surrey, England":"Farnham, Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wingrave, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wingrave, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"